ce:section.ce:para:
In the literature, heat and mass transfer are often treated as analogous scalar quantities, enabling findings from one field to be applicable to the other. For instance, temperature (T) findings can be transferred to mass concentration (c), and heat flux (q) findings to mass flux (G) by substituting molecular diffusivity (α) with mass diffusivity (
                        D
                     ) and setting the heat capacity (cp
                     ) to one. Dimensionless numbers can also be used interchangeably; for example, the Nusselt number (Nu) can be used in place of the Schmidt number (Sc), and the Stanton number (St) can be substituted for the Sherwood number (Sh). Mass transfer is particularly crucial in ABL flows, where interactions with surfaces such as water, land, vegetation, sand, and urban areas involve the transfer of momentum, heat, and mass. This area of study, known as interfacial transport phenomena, plays a significant role in the global balance of gases such as carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxides, and dimethyl sulfide [130–145]. Given that much of the existing literature emphasizes heat transfer, this study also prioritizes heat transfer analysis to build on and contribute to the established body of knowledge. Nonetheless, the principles and findings are equally relevant to scalar transport such as mass transfer.

Pioneering studies by Hagen [148] and Darcy [149] established the influence of surface roughness on pressure drop, which they attributed to increased drag force and blockage effects [150]. In the 1930s, Nikuradse's experiments [151] laid the foundation for roughness models by providing detailed measurements of friction factors and velocity profiles in pipes with sand-grain roughness. Building on this concept, Colebrook and White [152,153] developed the widely used Colebrook-White equation to calculate the Darcy friction factor in rough pipes. In 1937, Schlichting further advanced the field by introducing the concept of equivalent sand-grain roughness (ks
                        ) to quantify the effect of surface roughness on turbulent flows. Since then, ks
                         has been widely utilised as a rough flow length scale in related studies. More information can be found in Kadivar et al. [52] and Chung et al. [51].

According to Chung et al. [51], an accurate evaluation of sand-grain roughness (ks
                        ), and thus drag and heat transfer coefficients, requires including one roughness parameter from each category (height, spatial, and spectral). Skewness, along with effective slope and RMS height (Sq
                        ), are previously used in correlating roughness topology to ks
                         [117,167,286–288]. Compared to Gaussian surfaces, positive skewness increases friction drag, while negative skewness reduces friction drag [248,254,287]. The former is due to increased form drag, while the latter is due to the skimming effect [288], where the flow slides over abundant roughness valleys. Busse & Jelly [267] demonstrated that further increases in skewness beyond certain levels do not significantly affect the drag produced by the surface. Additionally, while surfaces with extreme features (such as high kurtosis) can locally impact flow fields, these deviations affect only a small portion of the flow due to the relative sparseness of such extreme features.

The primary distinction between heat transfer and momentum transfer lies in the absence of an analogous relationship for heat transfer, similar to the direct pressure-drag analogy in momentum transfer. In the fully rough regime, unlike the wall shear stress (τ
                        w
                     ), the wall heat flux (qw
                     ) does not scale with the inertial flow governed by the roughness elements (y/ks
                     ). Instead, qw
                      remains sensitive to the Prandtl number, alongside the characteristics of the flow itself. This difference underscores the separate impacts of roughness and molecular properties on convective heat transfer under fully rough conditions.
